Question - 1
Verify your current working directory ? 
Command: pwd
Description: pwd will print the current working directory
Question 2:
List "/etc" directory files and directories ?
Command: ls /etc
Description: ls command will list files and directories under given directory
Question 3:
List ".conf" files only under "/etc" directory ?
Command: ls -l /etc/*.conf
Description: ls command will list the contents under /etc directory and if we will pass pattern like *.(string) , it will look for all the files having matching string at the end of every file name
Question 4:
Print total number of ".conf" files only under "/etc" directory ?
Command: ls -l /etc/*.conf | wc -l
Description: ls command will list files under /etc directory and *.conf will filter all files having extension as .conf , using pipe separator we can call wc -l command to print the total number of files having .conf extension
Question 5:
Create an empty directory with name "autopilot" under "/tmp" directory ?
Command: mkdir /tmp/autopilot
Description: mkdir will create the empty directory with given name
Question 6:
Create an empty file with name "devops.txt" under "/tmp/autopilot/" directory ?
Command: touch /tmp/autopilot/devops.txt
Description: touch command will create an empty file under given path with given name
Question 7:
Change (Switch) your directory to "/tmp/autopilot/" ?
Command: cd /tmp/autopilot/
Description: cd command is used to change the directory, using cd we can switch to the given path
Question 8:
Switch your directory to /tmp/autopilot and then print "Hello Devops" into the "devops.txt" file in the "/tmp/autopilot" directory ?
Command: cd /tmp/autopilot/ ; echo "Hello Devops" > devops.txt
Description: echo command is used to print the message on screen , we can also use echo to print inside the given file, see the example above
Question 9:
Display the content of "/tmp/autopilot/devops.txt" file on screen ?
Command: cat devops.txt
Description: cat command will print the file content on screen
Question 10:
Switch your directory to /tmp/autopilot then Create a copy of "devops.txt" file and name the copy as "pilot.txt" ?
Command: cd /tmp/autopilot ; cp devops.txt pilot.txt
OR
Command: cp /tmp/autopilot/devops.txt /tmp/autopilot/pilot.txt (can be triggered without changing the directory)
Description: cp command is used to create a copy of source file , syntax of cp command: cp source_file destination_file
